## .NET MAUI Theme Detection & Override

### 1. Read the current system theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### 2. Subscribe to real-time theme changes

```csharp
// In App.xaml.cs or any page
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI on the main thread
    MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() =>
    {
        ApplyTheme(newTheme);
    });
};
```

### 3. Let the user force a specific theme

```csharp
// Force dark mode (ignores system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### 4. Respond in XAML with `AppThemeBinding`

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />

<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#FFFFFF, Dark=#1E1E1E}">
```

### Key points

| API | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `RequestedTheme` | Read-only; current OS theme |
| `RequestedThemeChanged` | Event fired when OS theme toggles |
| `UserAppTheme` | Read/write; set to override, `Unspecified` to follow OS |
| `AppThemeBinding` | XAML markup for automatic per-theme values |

Setting `UserAppTheme` takes precedence over the system theme and immediately updates any `AppThemeBinding` values in your UI. Setting it back to `AppTheme.Unspecified` resumes following the OS.
